# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1972-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1972-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1972-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1972-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1884 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished fifth in the American Association with a record of 68–41, 8 games behind the New York Metropolitans.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were looking to return to their 1882 form, when they won the American Association pennant before falling to third place in 1883.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club named pitcher Will White the player-manager for the 1884 season, taking over for catcher Pop Snyder.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season, although they did sign Tom Mansell, who had split the previous season between the Detroit Wolverines of the National League, and the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns of the AA, hitting .305 with 34 RBI and 45 runs between those two teams.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club also moved into American Park for the 1884 season.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly was the offensive force on the team, hitting .339 with eleven home runs and 91 RBI, all club highs.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones hit .314 with seven home runs and 71 RBI, along with a team high 117 runs.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White led the way with a 34–18 record and a 3.32 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati got off to a slow start, as they lost their first game in their new ballpark, 10–9 to the Columbus Buckeyes, and they had a record of 4–5 in their first nine games, before reeling off four wins in a row to stay above the .500 level for the rest of the season.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got red hot, as they eventually had a 28–14 record, only one game out of first place.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] In a three-game series against the Washington Nationals, the Red Stockings outscored their opposition 48–6.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started to fade as the season continued on, and with their record at 44–27 changed managers, bringing Pop Snyder back as player-manager.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati continued to slump, falling to 10½ games out of first place with a 52–35 record, but then won ten games in a row to climb back to within 4½ games.
[src:1972-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was too little too late though, as Cincinnati finished the season with a 68–41 record, good enough for fifth place, eight games behind the Metropolitans.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1885 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished second in the American Association, 16 games behind the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the Red Stockings hired O.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Caylor to become the manager of the team, the first time in club history that the club did not have a player-manager.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed Tony Mullane to a contract.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane, who spent the 1884 season with the Toledo Blue Stockings, had a 36–26 record with a 2.52 ERA in 67 starts, striking out 325 batters.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane was suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, as the Blue Stockings and the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons, another team he tried to sign with, folded after the 1884 season, and the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns attempted to reclaim Mullane, as he pitched there in 1883.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the Browns could reclaim him, he signed with the Red Stockings.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Frank Fennelly, who the Red Stockings acquired late in the 1884 season from the Washington Nationals, had a breakout season, hitting .273 with ten home runs and a league high 89 RBI.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones led the team with a .322 average, and had five home runs and 35 RBI to go along with it, while John Reilly hit .297 with five homers and 60 RBI.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Larry McKeon led the Red Stockings with 20 wins and a 2.86 ERA in 33 starts, while Will White had eighteen wins and a 3.53 ERA in 34 starts.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season very well, putting up an impressive 16–8 record in their first 24 games to sit in second place in the league, two games behind the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then began to slump, as they would win only six of their next sixteen games to slip into third place, seven games behind the Browns.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On July 1, the Red Stockings acquired Jim Keenan and Larry McKeon, who both jumped from the Detroit Wolverines to join Cincinnati.
[src:1972-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings improved with their new acquisitions in the lineup, as the team eventually moved back into second place, however, they were too far behind the Browns, and Cincinnati finished the season with a 63–49 record, good for second place, however, they were sixteen games out of first.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1972-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The **1972 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1972 season.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The 69th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the American League champion Oakland Athletics and the National League champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Athletics won in seven games for their sixth World Series championship.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] It was the first World Series championship for the Athletics since 1930.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship won by a team from the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] This was the first World Series in which both teams wore pullover jerseys, a style that would remain the norm until 1982, after which at least one team in the Fall Classic would wear them each year through 1990, after which traditional button-front jerseys once again predominated.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Coincidentally, both this World Series and the 1990 World Series featured the same two teams, the Athletics and the Reds, though with far different results; the Athletics won this one in a hard fought seven games, while the Reds swept the defending champion Athletics in four games in 1990.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Athletics won the American League West division by 5+1⁄2 games over the Chicago White Sox, then defeated the Detroit Tigers three games to two in the American League Championship Series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Cincinnati Reds won the National League West division by 10+1⁄2 games over both the Los Angeles Dodgers and the Houston Astros.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds dethroned the defending World Series champion Pittsburgh Pirates three games to two in the National League Championship Series, marking the first year in which an LCS series in either league went the full five games since divisional play was introduced in 1969.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds (95–59 (.617)) won one fewer game than the Pirates (96–59 (.619)) during the strike-reduced regular season and became the first team in MLB history to reach the World Series without having the best record in its respective league.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In each of the first six League Championship Series, the team with the better record advanced to the World Series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] This was Cincinnati's second trip to the World Series in three years, previously falling to Baltimore in five games in the 1970 World Series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] It was Oakland's first-ever trip to the Series, and the first for the franchise since 1931, when the team was located in Philadelphia.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] This was a matchup of the two premier MLB dynasties of the 1970s, with the Reds winning two World Series (1975–76) in four WS appearances, while the Athletics won three straight (1972–74).
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Oakland played the Series without its star outfielder Reggie Jackson, who was injured (pulled hamstring) stealing home in the second inning of the final game of the ALCS at Detroit on October 12.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Left-handed reliever Darold Knowles was also missing for the Athletics, breaking his thumb on September 27, less than three weeks before the Series opener.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] With Jackson out, the Athletics were decided underdogs.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] George Hendrick was inserted into center field for Jackson.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] And while Hendrick only went 2-for-15 (.133), unheralded catcher Gene Tenace stepped up.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Tenace had a poor regular season, hitting only .225 with just five home runs and 32 RBI in 82 games played.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] He was even worse in the AL Championship series against Detroit, going 1 for 17 (.059), although his one hit drove in the go-ahead run in Game 5.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In the World Series however, Tenace was spectacular, hitting four home runs equaling the World Series mark set by Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, and Hank Bauer.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] He also had nine RBI in the Series—no other Oakland player had more than one.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] By contrast, the stellar Oakland pitching kept the middle of the Reds lineup quiet for most of the series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Johnny Bench (.270 avg., 40 HR, 125 RBI, NL MVP), Tony Pérez (.283 avg., 21 HR, 90 RBI), and Denis Menke (9 HR, 50 RBI), combined for only two homers and five RBI the entire Series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Perez did lead both teams with 10 hits and a .435 batting average, but 8 of his 10 hits were singles.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] It didn't help that the Reds' "table-setters," Pete Rose and Joe Morgan were a combined 1 for 28 through the first four games, when the Reds lost three of those games.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The teams were fairly equal statistically, each club totaling 46 hits with the same .209 batting average (the combined batting averages were the lowest recorded in a 7-game World Series).
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds outscored the Athletics by five runs, 21–16, but all four of their losses were by a single run.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Six of the seven games in the series were decided by one run, marking perhaps the most closely contested World Series in history.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Oakland jumped out to a one-game series lead behind catcher Gene Tenace, who hit a home run in each of his first two at-bats.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Tenace became the first player ever to homer in his two initial Series plate appearances, a feat later matched by Andruw Jones of the Atlanta Braves in 1996.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Only two Oakland players collected hits, a pair each from Tenace and Bert Campaneris.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Athletics received a combined four innings of shutout relief from Rollie Fingers and Vida Blue to secure the victory for starter Ken Holtzman.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Blue stranded the potential tying run at third base to end the game by inducing Pete Rose to ground out to second base.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Game 2 hero was Athletics left fielder Joe Rudi, who smacked a home run and added a sparkling, game-saving catch up against the wall in the ninth inning on a ball hit by Denis Menke.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Catfish Hunter pitched eight strong innings, consistently wiggling out of trouble, and also added an RBI single in the second off Ross Grimsley.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds' failure to produce in the clutch was as much the story as Rudi's heroics as Cincinnati had leadoff baserunners in five innings but only scored a run in the ninth.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Athletics scored a run in the second when George Hendrick beat out a double-play grounder after Sal Bando led off with a single.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Hendrick went to second on a Dick Green single and scored on a close play at the plate on a Hunter single.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Bert Campaneris followed with a hit and Green attempted to score, but was successfully thrown out at the plate by Pete Rose.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Athletics had four hits in the inning, but only scored one run.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Rudi extended the lead to 2–0 with his home run in the 3rd.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In the ninth, Tony Pérez led off with a base hit before Rudi's catch of Menke's drive for the first out.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Oakland first baseman Mike Hegan then made another great defensive play when César Gerónimo, the next Reds hitter, lined a shot that appeared headed down the line for extra bases.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Hegan dove for the ball, knocked it down, and dove for the bag, barely beating Geronimo.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Pérez took second and scored on a Hal McRae single through the middle.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Rollie Fingers then relieved Hunter and induced pinch hitter Julián Javier to pop out to Hegan in foul territory to end the game.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The World Series home loss was Reds' seventh-straight, which included three in the 1961 World Series against the New York Yankees (at Crosley Field) and two in the 1970 World Series against the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Prior to the game Jackie Robinson, the first black major league player of the modern era, made his final public appearance (he died nine days later) in an on-field ceremony to mark the 25th anniversary of his breaking of the color line.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Former Reds radio announcer Red Barber, who had been with the Brooklyn Dodgers' broadcast crew for Robinson's inaugural 1947 season with that team, hosted the ceremony.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In a brief speech (following introductory remarks by MLB commissioner Bowie Kuhn), Robinson expressed his desire to see a black manager in the majors, a color barrier that hadn't yet been broken.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Two years later, Frank Robinson was hired in October 1974 to manage the Cleveland Indians to break that barrier.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Heavy storms delayed Game 3 by a day, but the Reds got back into the series behind a strong performance from starter Jack Billingham, who held the Athletics to three hits in eight innings.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds pushed across the game's only run in the seventh when César Gerónimo singled home Tony Pérez.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Pérez scored despite slipping on the still damp grass as he rounded third.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Oakland shortstop Bert Campaneris was apparently unaware that Pérez had slipped; otherwise, it appeared Campaneris may have had a play at the plate.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Clay Carroll pitched the ninth for the save.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] A rare trick play occurred in the eighth inning.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds had Joe Morgan on third and Bobby Tolan on first base with Rollie Fingers pitching to NL MVP Johnny Bench.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Fingers pitched carefully to Bench before Tolan stole second base on ball three.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] After the stolen base, with the count 3–2 on Bench, Athletics manager Dick Williams visited the mound.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] After a long discussion, he motioned for an intentional walk to Bench.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Athletics catcher Gene Tenace stood to catch ball four, but at the last second returned to his crouch as Fingers delivered a strike on the outside corner.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Bench watched the pitch go by for strike three.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Gene Tenace and Oakland non-starters put the Athletics up 3 games to 1.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The game was a pitchers' duel between a pair of left-handed starters: Cincinnati's Don Gullett and Oakland's Ken Holtzman.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Through seven innings, the game's lone run was a result of a fifth-inning home run by Tenace, his third homer of the series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] With two outs in the top of the eighth inning and Dave Concepción on second base, Athletics manager Dick Williams replaced Holtzman with left-hander Vida Blue to face left-handed hitters Joe Morgan and Bobby Tolan.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Blue walked Morgan and allowed a clutch two-run double to Tolan, giving Cincinnati the lead as the Reds seemed poised to tie the series at 2 games apiece.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, however, with one out, the Athletics strung together four consecutive hits to score two runs.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] It was the first time that a team collected three pinch hits in the same World Series inning.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Up three games to one and with ace Catfish Hunter on the mound, the Athletics looked poised to close out Cincinnati.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Compounding problems for the Reds, their ace pitcher Gary Nolan, who had been battling shoulder and neck issues during the second half of the regular season, was unable to pitch Game 5, forcing part-time starter Jim McGlothlin to start instead.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] But two of the struggling Reds, Pete Rose and Joe Morgan who were a combined 1 for 28 at the plate in the first four games, stepped up to make key plays.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Rose led off the game with a home run, and he would also drive in the game-winning run in the ninth inning.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The game ended dramatically when Morgan threw out the potential game-tying run at the plate as the Reds staved off elimination.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Trailing 1–0 in the second, Gene Tenace hit his fourth home run of the series, a three-run shot, to put Oakland up by two.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] McGlothlin was removed after pitching just three innings.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds cut the lead to 3–2 in the fourth on a home run by Denis Menke.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Gonzalo Marquez put the Athletics back in front by two runs with a pinch-hit RBI single in the fourth.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] With two outs in the fifth, Joe Morgan walked.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] On the first pitch to Bobby Tolan, Morgan broke for second and was able to score when Tolan lined a base hit into right-center field.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The speedy Morgan and Tolan collaborated once again in the eighth.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Morgan again walked, stole second and scored on another Tolan single to tie the game at four.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In the ninth, Rose singled in the go-ahead run to give the Reds a 5–4 lead.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Game 3 starter Jack Billingham came in to relieve in the ninth, but the Athletics put runners on the corners with one out.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Bert Campaneris hit a foul pop behind first base that Tony Pérez drifted back and appeared to call for.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] But second baseman Morgan raced over, waved Perez off, caught the ball, slipped on the grass but got up and fired a throw to nail pinch runner Blue Moon Odom, who had tagged from third.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Friday afternoon contest was the last non-weekend World Series day game.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The three games in Oakland had all been scheduled to be played at night, but Game 3 was rained out, forcing Game 5 to be played on a Friday, originally scheduled as a travel day.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The game was played in the afternoon (1 p.m.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] PT) to allow ample time for the teams to travel to Cincinnati for Game 6 the next day.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Back at the friendly confines of Riverfront Stadium, the Reds tied the series at three games apiece with a rout.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Johnny Bench, who had no RBIs in the series to that point, broke a scoreless tie in the fourth with a homer off starter Vida Blue.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Athletics fought back on a Dick Green RBI double in their half of the fifth, but from then on it was all Reds.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Dave Concepción had a sacrifice fly in the fifth, and Tony Pérez an RBI single in the sixth (his first RBI of the Series).
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds then broke it open with a five-run seventh, an RBI single by Joe Morgan and a pair of two-run singles by Bobby Tolan and César Gerónimo.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The win was the Reds' first World Series victory at home since Game 7 of the 1940 World Series, snapping a 7-game losing streak in World Series home games, which is tied for the longest such streak in MLB history (Cubs from 1918–1935).
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Prior to the game, an intoxicated Reds fan was caught trying to enter Riverfront Stadium with a loaded gun in his pocket, threatening to shoot Gene Tenace if he hit another home run.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Gene Tenace capped a spectacular World Series with two hits, two RBI and he also scored the game-winning run in the sixth inning on Sal Bando's double.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Oakland scored an unearned run in the first inning off Jack Billingham when Reds center fielder Bobby Tolan misplayed a fly ball by Mangual into a three-base error.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Mangual scored on a two-out single by Tenace on a ball that hit a seam in the Astroturf and bounced over the head of third baseman Denis Menke.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds tied the game in the fifth on a bases loaded sacrifice fly to the center field wall by Hal McRae.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] However, McRae was pinch hitting for Billingham who had allowed no earned runs in 13+2⁄3 innings in the series against the Athletics.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] His replacement in the sixth inning, Pedro Borbón, surrendered RBI doubles to Tenace and Bando.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Bando's drive appeared catchable, but Tolan pulled up short of the wall due to a strained hamstring and the ball went over Tolan to the base of the wall.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] He was later removed from the game on a double switch.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds closed to within 3–2 in the eighth on a sacrifice fly by Perez.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In the ninth inning, Athletics closer Rollie Fingers retired the first two hitters, César Gerónimo and Dave Concepción, before Darrel Chaney was hit by pitch.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] That created a rare "golden pitch" situation whereby either team could win on the next pitch.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] However, on the first pitch of the at-bat, Pete Rose lined out to left field to end the game, and the A's clinched their first championship in 42 years.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Source: This was the second of three consecutive years in which the World Series went seven games and the champion was outscored.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Six of the games were decided by one run, the sole exception was Game 6, an 8–1 Reds' win.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] NBC aired the series on both television and radio.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Curt Gowdy (on television) and Jim Simpson (on radio) alternated play-by-play with team announcers Al Michaels (Reds) and Monte Moore (Athletics).
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Tony Kubek, who had served as an in-the-stands reporter for NBC's four previous World Series telecasts, was promoted to the booth as a color analyst, becoming the first former player to serve in that capacity on a Series telecast since Joe Garagiola in 1961.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Michaels was, at 27, the second youngest person to call play-by-play of a World Series telecast.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Only Vin Scully, who called the 1953 World Series at 25, was younger.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Joe Buck would tie Michaels when he called the 1996 World Series, also at age 27; but unlike Michaels and Scully, who only called parts of the telecast, Buck did play-by-play for every inning of every game.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Hall of Famer and Civil Rights trailblazer Jackie Robinson died of a heart attack two days after the series ended.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Robinson had thrown out the first pitch in Game 2 in the World Series.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] In addressing the crowd, he said he hoped to see a black MLB manager soon.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Frank Robinson, no relation, achieved that in 1974.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The World Series victory for the Oakland Athletics was the first for the franchise since the days of Connie Mack when the team was in Philadelphia and had won in 1930.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The victory ensured manager Dick Williams' return for another year.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] It was the Athletics' sixth World Series title, and the first of three consecutive titles.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] This was the last time to date that an American League team had won a World Series Game 7 on the road until 2017, when the Houston Astros did so in Los Angeles.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] The Reds would go on to form a dynasty of their own, becoming the third NL team (following the Chicago Cubs in 1907–08 and the New York Giants in 1921–22) to win consecutive World Series in 1975 and 1976.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] These two teams met again in the World Series 18 years later in 1990.
[src:1972-world-series/1972-world-series] Their managers would meet again in the Fall Classic 12 years later in 1984, helming different teams and swapping leagues.
